note._content: This heritage-listed Italianate late Victorian mansion,Ashbourne was built for Walter German c1890-91.German was Mayor of Manly in the 1890s.Later Ashbourne became a private hospital,nursing home and finally workmens' boardinghouse.In 2009,Manly Council approved a major redevelopment/adaptive reuse.
note.author: 39165494@N06

note._content: Photo taken from high side of Osborne Road,Manly looking south-west  down an unmade Marshall Street to Wood Street and out over Little Manly Cove and Manly Point.Ashbourne,built c1890-91 is right foreground.
note.author: 39165494@N06

note._content: Little Manly Wharf built in 1887 for John Murray,a competitor of the dominant Port Jackson Steamship Co. who controlled the main Manly Wharf in Manly Cove.
note.author: 39165494@N06

note._content: Uyeno,designed and built by the architect,John Smedley c1883(Sands 1884).It was later renamed Glanwyre and was for many years owned by the Holt family.Today's Kilburn Towers on Manly Point (formerly known as Smedley's Point)was built on portion of the former Glanwyre Estate.
note.author: 39165494@N06

note._content: "Maretimo",built c1885-86,for a prominent Manly alderman and Mayor,and city businessman,Ald Griffin.Maretimo was one of several harbourside mansions with waterfront estates built in Addison Road,Manly during the land boom of the 1880s.These included Uyeno,Maretimo,Oyama,Kulnura,Weemala and Calmar.
note.author: 39165494@N06

note._content: Little Manly Cove,current site of Little Manly's harbour baths and boat ramp.
note.author: 39165494@N06

note._content: Little Manly or Gasworks Point,site for many years of Manly's Gas Works
